Functions in Biological Modeling

  • A function is a mathematical relationship between two variables, typically denoted as \(f(x)\).

  • \(f(x)\) takes input \(x\) and produces output \(f(x)\).

  • The mathematical notion of a function is not entirely different from the programming concept of a function (but also not entirely the same).

Mathematical Functions vs Programming Functions

  • Mathematical Functions: A relationship between two variables, typically denoted as \(f(x)\).

  • Programming Functions: A block of code that can be used to perform a specific task.

  • Similarities: Both take input and produce output.

  • Differences: Mathematical functions are subject to more constraints than programming functions. E.g., the must be one-to-one such that \(f(x)\) is unique for each for each \(x\).

X-Axis Translation

  • \(f(x+a)\) slides the shape of the function \(f(x)\) to the left along the x-axis by \(a\) units.

X-Axis Translation

  • \(f(x-a)\) slides the shape of the function \(f(x)\) to the right along the x-axis by \(a\) units.

Y-Axis Translation

  • \(f(x)+a\) slides the shape of the function \(f(x)\) up along the y-axis by \(a\) units.

Y-Axis Translation

  • \(f(x)-a\) slides the shape of the function \(f(x)\) down along the y-axis by \(a\) units.

Reflections

  • \(f(-x)\) reflects the shape of the function \(f(x)\) in the y-axis.

Reflections

  • \(-f(x)\) reflects the shape of the function \(f(x)\) in the x-axis.
